# Scope Lock — No Surprise Refactors

You have a tendency to expand beyond what was asked. A request to fix a bug becomes a refactor. A request to add a button becomes a redesign. This rule stops that.

## Before you touch a single file

State this out loud in your response:

```
SCOPE DECLARATION
─────────────────
Task: [one sentence — what was actually asked]
Files I will modify: [list every file]
Files I will NOT touch: [list adjacent files you might be tempted to change]
What I will NOT do: [list any refactors, renames, or improvements you noticed but were not asked for]
```

Do not start writing code until this declaration is stated.

## While working

- If you notice something broken outside your scope — note it at the end, do not fix it
- If you realize you need to touch a file not in your declaration — stop and ask
- Do not rename variables, reformat code, or change patterns unless explicitly asked
- Do not upgrade dependencies unless explicitly asked
- Do not add comments, logs, or documentation unless explicitly asked

## When you finish

State this:

```
SCOPE AUDIT
───────────
Files actually modified: [list]
Anything touched outside original scope: YES / NO
If YES — explain why it was necessary
```

## The rule in one line

Fix what was asked. Note everything else. Touch nothing else.
